+# Chat Web Data System Performance Report
+
+Date: 2026-05-08  
+Scope: Analysis only. No code changes, no host gateway restart.
+
+## Executive Summary
+
+The Chat Web app feels slow mainly because navigation and reload paths do too much synchronous data work. The most expensive paths are not simple SQLite session-name lookups; they are combined bootstrap operations that still touch multiple stores, compute unread counts, and sometimes scan Pi Coding Agent JSONL session files.
+
+Key findings:
+
+- `/api/chat/bootstrap` is too heavy for room switching and page refresh.
+- Pi Coding Agent JSONL session metadata remains on the hot path when Pibo session titles are missing.
+- Unread-count calculation is currently expensive on the production data set.
+- Chat/Pibo events are stored redundantly in multiple SQLite tables and Pi JSONL transcripts.
+- The production SQLite files are heavily bloated, with large WAL files and high freelist counts.
+
+## Current Data Stores
+
+| Store | Path | Purpose |
+|---|---|---|
+| Pibo Session Store | `/root/.pibo/pibo-sessions.sqlite` | Product-level Pibo sessions, owner, room metadata, profile, title, linked Pi session id |
+| Chat Web DB | `/root/.pibo/web-chat.sqlite` | Rooms, room members, chat events, read model sessions/events, read cursors |
+| Pibo Event Store | `/root/.pibo/pibo-events.sqlite` | Product event stream, jobs, runs |
+| Pi JSONL Sessions | `/root/.pi/agent/sessions/.../*.jsonl` | Pi Coding Agent transcript/session files |
+| Auth DB | `/root/.pibo/auth.sqlite` | Better Auth state |
+| Custom Agents DB | `/root/.pibo/chat-agents.sqlite` | Custom agent definitions |
+
+## Data Flow Overview
+
+```mermaid
+flowchart TD
+    UI[Chat Web UI<br/>React App] -->|GET /api/chat/bootstrap| Bootstrap[Chat Web API Bootstrap]
+    UI -->|GET /api/chat/trace| TraceAPI[Trace API]
+    UI -->|SSE /api/chat/events| EventSSE[Live Event Stream]
+
+    Bootstrap --> Auth[Better Auth Session]
+    Bootstrap --> SessionStore[Pibo Session Store<br/>pibo-sessions.sqlite]
+    Bootstrap --> RoomStore[Room Store<br/>web-chat.sqlite / pibo_rooms]
+    Bootstrap --> ReadModel[Chat Read Model<br/>web-chat.sqlite / web_chat_sessions]
+    Bootstrap --> EventLog[Chat Event Log<br/>web-chat.sqlite / chat_events]
+    Bootstrap --> Catalog[Profiles / Agents / Models / Capabilities]
+    Bootstrap --> PiJSONL[Pi Session JSONL<br/>~/.pi/agent/sessions/.../*.jsonl]
+
+    TraceAPI --> ReadModel
+    TraceAPI --> EventLog
+    TraceAPI --> PiJSONL
+    TraceAPI --> TraceBuilder[Trace Builder<br/>buildTraceView]
+
+    Runtime[Pibo / Pi Runtime] -->|output events| PiboEvents[pibo-events.sqlite<br/>pibo_event_stream]
+    Runtime -->|persist transcript| PiJSONL
+    Runtime -->|indexed output| ReadModel
+    Runtime -->|chat/event stream| EventLog
+
+    EventSSE --> EventLog
+    EventSSE --> UI
+
+    SessionStore --> Bootstrap
+    RoomStore --> Bootstrap
+    ReadModel --> Bootstrap
+    EventLog --> Bootstrap
+    Catalog --> Bootstrap
+    PiJSONL --> Bootstrap
+```
+
+## Production Measurements
+
+Measured against `/root/.pibo` and `/root/.pi/agent/sessions` on 2026-05-08.
+
+### Store Sizes
+
+| File | Size |
+|---|---:|
+| `/root/.pibo/web-chat.sqlite` | 1.73 GB |
+| `/root/.pibo/web-chat.sqlite-wal` | 348 MB |
+| `/root/.pibo/pibo-events.sqlite` | 923 MB |
+| `/root/.pibo/pibo-events.sqlite-wal` | 432 MB |
+| `/root/.pibo/pibo-sessions.sqlite` | 209 KB |
+| `/root/.pibo/pibo-sessions.sqlite-wal` | 515 KB |
+
+### SQLite Row Counts
+
+| Table | Count | Count Query Time |
+|---|---:|---:|
+| `pibo_sessions` | 228 | 4.1 ms |
+| `web_chat_sessions` | 228 | 0.5 ms |
+| `web_chat_events` | 69,110 | 284.2 ms |
+| `chat_events` | 69,968 | 702.0 ms |
+| `pibo_event_stream` | 90,766 | 199.4 ms |
+
+### DB Bloat Indicators
+
+| DB | `page_count` | `freelist_count` | Approx Free Space |
+|---|---:|---:|---:|
+| `web-chat.sqlite` | 422,601 | 342,665 | ~1.4 GB |
+| `pibo-events.sqlite` | 225,360 | 182,402 | ~747 MB |
+
+This suggests large amounts of deleted/free pages remain inside the SQLite files. This does not by itself prove request slowness, but it increases file size, backup size, checkpoint cost, and potential I/O/cache pressure.
+
+### Session Distribution
+
+| Metric | Value |
+|---|---:|
+| Total Pibo sessions | 228 |
+| Main owner sessions | 225 |
+| Sessions in room `Pibo Source` | 222 |
+| Sessions missing title | 106 |
+| Main owner sessions missing title | 103 |
+| Workspace `/root/code/pibo` sessions | 214 |
+| Workspace `/root/code/pibo` sessions missing title | 95 |
+
+### Pi JSONL Session Files
+
+| Directory | Files | Total Size | Largest File |
+|---|---:|---:|---:|
+| `/root/.pi/agent/sessions/--root-code-pibo--` | 195 | 126 MB | 4.79 MB |
+| `/root/.pi/agent/sessions/--root--` | 46 | 19.2 MB | 3.19 MB |
+
+Benchmarks:
+
+| Operation | Time |
+|---|---:|
+| `SessionManager.list('/root/code/pibo')` first run | 3.3 s |
+| `SessionManager.list('/root/code/pibo')` second run | 2.2 s |
+| Read + parse largest JSONL file, 4.79 MB | 108 ms |
+
+## Hot Path Analysis
+
+### `/api/chat/bootstrap`
+
+Code path: `src/apps/chat/web-app.ts`, route `/api/chat/bootstrap`.
+
+The bootstrap handler performs all of the following in one request:
+
+1. Auth session lookup.
+2. Resolve selected Pibo session.
+3. Ensure/default room handling.
+4. Load all owned sessions.
+5. Filter visible sessions by room/archive state.
+6. Optionally mark the selected session subtree as read.
+7. Upsert session metadata into the read model.
+8. Compute unread counts.
+9. Build session nodes.
+10. Load bootstrap catalog: profiles, custom agents, model defaults, model catalog, agent catalog, capabilities.
+11. Load room tree and room unread counts.
+12. Return one large combined payload.
+
+This is too much work for a request that is called on initial page load and room switching.
+
+### Unread Count Query
+
+Code path: `src/apps/chat/event-log.ts`, `countUnreadMessagesBySession()`.
+
+Measured on 225 sessions:
+
+```text
+countUnreadMessagesBySession all ids: 4306.4 ms
+result: counted 0, total unread 0
+```
+
+Even with batching, the query is expensive because it scans session event ranges, checks read cursors, filters chat-message events, uses `COUNT(DISTINCT ...)`, and performs an `EXISTS` correlation to verify completed assistant messages.
+
+This is likely the largest direct contributor to slow room switching and refresh.
+
+### JSONL Session Metadata in Bootstrap
+
+Code path: `src/apps/chat/trace.ts`, `buildSessionNodes()` and `listPiSessions()`.
+
+If a Pibo session has no stored title, `buildSessionNodes()` falls back to Pi JSONL metadata. It may call `SessionManager.list(cwd)`, which reads and parses all JSONL session files in the workspace directory.
+
+On the production data set, `SessionManager.list('/root/code/pibo')` takes 2.2–3.3 seconds.
+
+This means the old Pi session-file model is still on the Chat Web navigation path when titles are missing.
+
+### Trace Loading
+
+Code path: `src/apps/chat/web-app.ts`, route `/api/chat/trace`.
+
+Trace loading is less problematic than bootstrap, but still does work across multiple sources:
+
+- selected Pibo session from session store,
+- read model event query,
+- chat event latest stream id,
+- Pi JSONL metadata/transcript parsing,
+- trace view construction.
+
+Measured for the latest session:
+
+| Operation | Time |
+|---|---:|
+| latest event sequence | 0.7 ms |
+| latest stream id | 0.1 ms |
+| trace event list | 40 ms |
+
+Trace is not the primary bottleneck in the current measurements, but larger sessions and cache misses can make it noticeable.
+
+## Pi Coding Agent Session Model
+
+Pi Coding Agent itself stores sessions as JSONL files under:
+
+```text
+~/.pi/agent/sessions/--<cwd>--/<timestamp>_<uuid>.jsonl
+```
+
+Important properties:
+
+- One Pi session equals one JSONL file.
+- Independent sessions are not merged into one shared JSONL file.
+- Branching inside a session uses `id` / `parentId` entries in the same file.
+- `/tree` keeps alternatives in the same file.
+- `/fork`, `/clone`, and `newSession()` create new JSONL files.
+- Forked sessions include `parentSession` in the header.
+
+### Pi JSONL Shape
+
+The first line is a session header:
+
+```json
+{"type":"session","version":3,"id":"uuid","timestamp":"2026-05-08T10:00:00.000Z","cwd":"/root/code/pibo"}
+```
+
+Forked/derived sessions may include:
+
+```json
+{"parentSession":"/path/to/original/session.jsonl"}
+```
+
+Subsequent lines are entries, for example:
+
+```json
+{"type":"message","id":"a1b2c3d4","parentId":null,"timestamp":"...","message":{"role":"user","content":"Hello"}}
+```
+
+```json
+{"type":"message","id":"b2c3d4e5","parentId":"a1b2c3d4","timestamp":"...","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hi"}],"provider":"openai","model":"...","usage":{},"stopReason":"stop"}}
+```
+
+Other entry types include:
+
+- `model_change`
+- `thinking_level_change`
+- `compaction`
+- `branch_summary`
+- `custom`
+- `custom_message`
+- `label`
+- `session_info`
+
+The JSONL model is simple and robust, but full listing scales poorly because Pi must read and parse files to build session metadata.
+
+## Root-Cause Summary
+
+The slow feeling is not caused by plain text being inherently large. It comes from the architecture and request shape:
+
+1. Bootstrap combines too many responsibilities.
+2. Navigation depends on expensive unread-count computation.
+3. Navigation can still depend on JSONL scanning when titles are missing.
+4. Event data is duplicated across `chat_events`, `web_chat_events`, `pibo_event_stream`, and Pi JSONL.
+5. SQLite files are bloated and WAL files are large.
+6. Synchronous SQLite work runs on the Node request path.
+
+## Recommendations
+
+No implementation was done. Suggested next steps:
+
+### Priority 1: Split Bootstrap
+
+Separate navigation-critical data from secondary data:
+
+- fast room/session list endpoint,
+- separate agent/model/capability catalog endpoint,
+- separate unread counts endpoint,
+- trace stays separate.
+
+Room switching should not reload the full application catalog.
+
+### Priority 2: Remove JSONL from Navigation
+
+Persist title, first message, modified time, and message count into SQLite/read model when sessions are created/updated.
+
+JSONL should remain a transcript/replay/fork source, not a navigation metadata source.
+
+### Priority 3: Materialize or Lazy-Load Unread Counts
+
+Options:
+
+- precomputed unread counters per session/user,
+- latest read stream plus incremental counters,
+- lazy fetch after navigation,
+- omit unread counts from blocking bootstrap.
+
+The measured 4.3 s unread query should not block room switching.
+
+### Priority 4: DB Maintenance Plan
+
+Investigate safe maintenance for production:
+
+- WAL checkpointing,
+- retention policy enforcement,
+- VACUUM or VACUUM INTO on backup copy,
+- compaction of duplicated event stores.
+
+Do this only with backups and controlled dev validation.
+
+### Priority 5: Add Server-Timing Instrumentation
+
+Add per-section timings for bootstrap:
+
+- auth,
+- resolve session,
+- list owned sessions,
+- unread counts,
+- build session nodes,
+- JSONL metadata,
+- catalog,
+- room tree,
+- response serialization.
+
+This would make future regressions visible immediately.
+
+## Conclusion
+
+The current architecture is a hybrid of Pi JSONL transcripts and multiple Pibo SQLite read/event stores. This is useful for compatibility and traceability, but it puts too much work on navigation requests.
+
+The highest-confidence bottlenecks are:
+
+1. unread-count calculation in bootstrap,
+2. Pi JSONL session listing for missing titles,
+3. oversized all-in-one bootstrap payload and responsibilities.
+
+Moving navigation metadata fully into SQLite and making bootstrap smaller should make room switching and refresh feel dramatically faster.
