+# Pibo Chat Memory / OOM Investigation — 2026-05-08
+
+Date: 2026-05-08  
+Scope: Investigation of a VM freeze / suspected out-of-memory incident shortly before 13:15 UTC.  
+Mode: Read-only investigation. No application code, database, gateway, or service changes were made.
+
+## Executive summary
+
+The incident looks like system-wide memory pressure and swap exhaustion, not a clean kernel OOM kill.
+
+At the time of the incident, the VM had about 3.8 GiB RAM and 4 GiB swap. `sar` data from the previous boot showed:
+
+```text
+13:10:34 UTC
+available memory: ~17 MB
+swap used: ~4.19 GB / 4.19 GB = 99.99%
+load average: 51.62
+```
+
+This explains why the machine became unreachable. It was likely swap-thrashing under memory pressure rather than immediately killing one process with the kernel OOM killer.
+
+No kernel log entries were found for `Out of memory`, `oom-killer`, or `Killed process` in the current or previous boot. The system did, however, log repeated memory-pressure events:
+
+```text
+systemd-journald: Under memory pressure, flushing caches.
+systemd-resolved: Under memory pressure, flushing caches.
+```
+
+The most likely cause was the combination of:
+
+1. high `pibo-web.service` memory peaks;
+2. multiple unbounded Docker compute containers;
+3. possible parallel `pibo-web` and `pibo-web-fallback` processes;
+4. active Agent/Pi runtimes that keep message/tool state in memory;
+5. no memory limits on systemd services or Docker workers.
+
+The older Chat Web performance issues can contribute to memory pressure through large temporary allocations and JSONL scans, but the acute incident appears to be a resource isolation problem.
+
+## Incident evidence
+
+### Boot timeline
+
+The VM was restarted at about 13:15 UTC.
+
+```text
+Previous boot: Mon 2026-05-04 21:34:43 UTC -> Fri 2026-05-08 13:11:12 UTC
+Current boot:  Fri 2026-05-08 13:15:00 UTC
+```
+
+### Memory and swap before reboot
+
+From `sar` for 2026-05-08:
+
+| Time | Available memory | Memory used | Swap used | Load avg 1m |
+|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|
+| 12:50:07 | ~326 MB | 82.84% | 79.93% | 4.13 |
+| 13:00:00 | ~435 MB | 79.17% | 81.32% | 4.54 |
+| 13:10:34 | ~17 MB | 92.18% | 99.99% | 51.62 |
+
+At 13:10 the machine had effectively exhausted swap and had a huge run queue. That is consistent with the observed complete unresponsiveness.
+
+### Kernel OOM logs
+
+No kernel OOM-killer evidence was found in either current or previous boot:
+
+```text
+journalctl -k -b    | grep -Ei 'out of memory|oom|killed process|invoked oom-killer'
+journalctl -k -b -1 | grep -Ei 'out of memory|oom|killed process|invoked oom-killer'
+```
+
+Both returned no relevant entries.
+
+This does not rule out memory exhaustion. It means the system likely became unresponsive through memory pressure and swap thrashing before a clean OOM-killer event was recorded.
+
+## Process and service findings
+
+### Current post-reboot memory state
+
+Shortly after reboot:
+
+```text
+RAM: 3.8 GiB total
+Swap: 4.0 GiB total, 0 used
+```
+
+Largest processes included:
+
+```text
+pibo-web.service node process: ~400-800 MB RSS during observation
+pibo-web-dev.service node process: ~140 MB RSS
+dockerd: ~100 MB RSS
+containerd: ~65 MB RSS
+Xvfb: ~67 MB RSS
+```
+
+`pibo-web.service` had already reached a current-boot `MemoryPeak` of about 1.1 GiB within minutes.
+
+### Historical `pibo-web.service` peaks
+
+`pibo-web.service` repeatedly reached high memory peaks before the incident:
+
+```text
+May 07 04:42  pibo-web peak 2.8G, swap 397M
+May 07 05:55  pibo-web peak 2.8G, swap 1.4G
+May 08 11:26  pibo-web peak 1.9G, swap 318M
+May 08 13:00  pibo-web peak 1.9G, swap 693M
+```
+
+These peaks are too high for a 3.8 GiB VM when Docker workers, browser automation, dev services, and system processes are also running.
+
+### `pibo-web-dev.service` peaks
+
+The dev gateway was smaller but still consumed memory and swap at times:
+
+```text
+May 08 07:21  pibo-web-dev peak 418.9M, swap 132.3M
+May 08 12:58  pibo-web-dev peak 188.3M, swap 82.6M
+```
+
+This is not the main culprit, but it contributes to total system pressure.
+
+### Fallback gateway risk
+
+`pibo-web.service` has:
+
+```ini
+Restart=always
+OnFailure=pibo-web-fallback.service
+```
+
+When `pibo-web.service` fails or is killed, systemd may start both:
+
+1. the normal `pibo-web.service`, due to `Restart=always`;
+2. `pibo-web-fallback.service`, due to `OnFailure=`.
+
+The logs show this happening:
+
+```text
+13:00:02 Started pibo-web-fallback.service
+13:00:02 Started pibo-web.service
+13:00:10 fallback: pibo chat app available
+13:00:11 main:     pibo chat app available
+```
+
+This can create two production-like gateways in parallel, each with its own router, runtime state, stores, caches, and memory footprint.
+
+The fallback service has also shown high historical memory peaks:
+
+```text
+pibo-web-fallback peak 2.6G
+pibo-web-fallback peak 1.7G
+```
+
+This is a significant stability risk.
+
+## Docker compute findings
+
+Before the reboot, several compute containers were running:
+
+```text
+pibo-worker-vewr0q8j
+projects-feature
+pibo-dev-project-2af2e7db-2fbf54d5
+signal-registry-recompute
+```
+
+All inspected containers had no memory limit:
+
+```text
+memoryLimit=0
+```
+
+This means Docker could consume host memory until the VM became unstable.
+
+One worker was created shortly before the incident:
+
+```text
+pibo-worker-vewr0q8j started at 13:03:22 UTC
+```
+
+The VM entered severe memory pressure by 13:10. This timing suggests the new worker and existing long-running workers contributed to the incident.
+
+The compute system currently starts containers without `--memory` / `--memory-swap` limits. On a small VM, multiple workers can exhaust memory even if the production gateway itself is not leaking.
+
+## Memory model: what is loaded and retained
+
+There are two different types of "session" memory to distinguish.
+
+### 1. Pibo session metadata
+
+Stored in:
+
+```text
+/root/.pibo/pibo-sessions.sqlite
+```
+
+Contains small product metadata:
+
+```text
+id
+piSessionId
+title
+roomId
+profile
+ownerScope
+timestamps
+metadata
+```
+
+Bootstrap loads many or all owner session metadata rows as normal JavaScript objects. This is temporary per request and should normally be garbage-collected after the response, unless retained in a cache or closure.
+
+Bootstrap does not create a full Agent runtime for every session.
+
+### 2. RoutedSession / Agent runtime
+
+Stored in memory by:
+
+```ts
+PiboSessionRouter.sessions = new Map<string, RoutedSession>()
+```
+
+A `RoutedSession` is heavy. It holds:
+
+- `AgentSessionRuntime`;
+- Pi agent session state;
+- `runtime.session.messages`;
+- tool results and tool state;
+- context and resource loader state;
+- subscriptions;
+- pending queues;
+- active model/tool state.
+
+A `RoutedSession` is created when a session is actively used through router execution, for example:
+
+- sending a message;
+- running an action;
+- fork/clone;
+- tree navigation;
+- model change;
+- compaction;
+- kill/dispose actions.
+
+It is not created by normal bootstrap for every listed session.
+
+### Current retention behavior
+
+`PiboSessionRouter.sessions` has no visible idle TTL or LRU eviction. A `RoutedSession` remains in memory until one of these happens:
+
+- explicit dispose;
+- kill/killAll in relevant paths;
+- router shutdown;
+- selected reset paths such as fork/clone reset.
+
+There is no automatic cleanup such as:
+
+```text
+if session is idle for N minutes and not processing:
+  dispose runtime
+  delete from sessions map
+```
+
+This means active sessions can accumulate over time and retain full message/tool state in memory.
+
+## Bootstrap behavior and memory impact
+
+Bootstrap does load the full owned-session metadata set for the user, but not all heavy Agent runtimes.
+
+Current bootstrap path includes:
+
+```text
+GET /api/chat/bootstrap
+  -> auth session lookup
+  -> resolve selected Pibo session
+  -> select/default room handling
+  -> list owned Pibo sessions
+  -> filter visible sessions by room/archive state
+  -> maybe mark selected session subtree as read
+  -> upsert session metadata into read model
+  -> compute unread counts
+  -> build session nodes
+       -> may call Pi SessionManager.list(cwd) if titles are missing
+  -> load room tree and room unread counts
+  -> load profile/agent/model/capability catalog
+  -> return combined payload
+```
+
+Memory implications:
+
+1. Session metadata arrays are temporary but can be large during the request.
+2. Unread-count queries can allocate result sets and temporary SQLite structures.
+3. Missing titles can trigger `SessionManager.list(cwd)`, which scans/parses JSONL transcripts and can allocate large temporary structures.
+4. Catalog loading and trace construction can add temporary allocations.
+
+This can cause large short-lived memory spikes. Those spikes become dangerous when the process already holds many active `RoutedSession`s or when Docker workers are consuming host memory.
+
+## Code areas that may hold or amplify memory
+
+### `PiboSessionRouter.sessions`
+
+File:
+
+```text
+src/core/session-router.ts
+```
+
+Relevant state:
+
+```ts
+private readonly sessions = new Map<string, RoutedSession>();
+private readonly pendingSessions = new Map<string, Promise<RoutedSession>>();
+```
+
+Risk: active runtimes are retained indefinitely unless explicitly disposed.
+
+### `RoutedSession` and Pi runtime messages
+
+File:
+
+```text
+src/core/routed-session.ts
+```
+
+The runtime keeps current agent messages and state. Large tool outputs, read results, bash logs, or subagent results can remain in memory as part of the active session.
+
+The compaction path estimates context size from:
+
+```ts
+session.messages
+```
+
+This confirms that the active Pi session keeps message objects in memory.
+
+### Runtime creation scans Pi JSONL
+
+File:
+
+```text
+src/core/runtime.ts
+```
+
+Current session manager creation can call:
+
+```ts
+const existing = (await SessionManager.list(cwd)).find((session) => session.id === profile.sessionId);
+```
+
+`SessionManager.list(cwd)` can scan and parse many JSONL files. This is both slow and memory-spiky.
+
+### Trace cache
+
+File:
+
+```text
+src/apps/chat/web-app.ts
+```
+
+State:
+
+```ts
+traceCache: Map<string, PiboSessionTraceView>
+TRACE_CACHE_MAX_ENTRIES = 24
+```
+
+The cache is bounded by entry count, not by bytes. Large trace views can consume significant memory even with only 24 entries.
+
+### Output compactor buffers
+
+File:
+
+```text
+src/apps/chat/output-compactor.ts
+```
+
+State:
+
+```ts
+assistantBuffers
+thinkingBuffers
+toolSnapshots
+```
+
+These buffers hold active streaming output and live tool snapshots. They normally flush at message boundaries, but failed or interrupted flows should be audited to ensure buffers always clear.
+
+### SSE listeners and active streams
+
+File:
+
+```text
+src/apps/chat/web-app.ts
+```
+
+State:
+
+```ts
+liveListeners: Set<(event: ChatLiveEvent) => void>
+activeEventStreams: Map<string, Map<string, string>>
+activeTraceSessions: Set<string>
+```
+
+SSE streams remove listeners on stream cancellation. If clients disconnect badly or streams are not cancelled promptly, listeners and active-stream metadata may be retained longer than expected.
+
+`activeTraceSessions` appears monotonic: sessions are added when router events are indexed and not removed. The set stores only IDs, so it is not a large memory consumer by itself, but it can affect logic over time.
+
+## Likely incident sequence
+
+The most plausible sequence is:
+
+1. `pibo-web.service` already had high memory usage or swap history.
+2. Multiple compute containers were running with no memory limits.
+3. A new worker started at 13:03 UTC.
+4. Docker/Xvfb/Node/Chrome/build-related processes increased total memory use.
+5. At 13:10 UTC, available memory dropped to about 17 MB and swap reached 99.99%.
+6. The load average jumped above 50.
+7. The VM became effectively unreachable.
+8. The VM was manually restarted.
+
+This is consistent with resource exhaustion and swap thrashing, not necessarily a single deterministic application leak.
+
+## Immediate operational mitigations
+
+### 1. Add memory limits to Docker compute workers
+
+Compute workers should not run with `memoryLimit=0` on a small VM.
+
+Recommended direction:
+
+```text
+pibo compute spawn/dev should set Docker --memory and --memory-swap.
+```
+
+Example policy:
+
+```text
+worker container: 768M-1.5G memory limit depending on VM size
+dev worker: explicit larger limit only when requested
+memory-swap: bounded, not unlimited
+```
+
+The exact values should be chosen after testing. The important rule is that compute workers must not be able to consume the entire host.
+
+### 2. Reap old compute containers
+
+Operationally:
+
+```text
+pibo compute list
+pibo compute release <id>
+pibo compute reap --max-age-minutes <n>
+```
+
+There were no running containers after reboot, but several exited containers remained. The bigger issue is that multiple long-running workers were active before the crash.
+
+### 3. Fix fallback service semantics
+
+Review the combination:
+
+```ini
+Restart=always
+OnFailure=pibo-web-fallback.service
+```
+
+This can start main and fallback in parallel. Options to evaluate:
+
+- remove `OnFailure` when `Restart=always` is active;
+- use fallback only after repeated start failures;
+- ensure fallback exits when main becomes healthy;
+- enforce port or lock ownership so only one production gateway can run;
+- add memory limits to both main and fallback.
+
+### 4. Add systemd memory limits
+
+Set protective limits so one service cannot freeze the whole VM.
+
+Candidate services:
+
+```text
+pibo-web.service
+pibo-web-dev.service
+pibo-web-fallback.service
+```
+
+Possible systemd settings to evaluate:
+
+```ini
+MemoryHigh=...
+MemoryMax=...
+MemorySwapMax=...
+OOMPolicy=stop
+```
+
+The goal is to restart or stop one service before the whole VM becomes unreachable.
+
+### 5. Add lightweight host monitoring
+
+Record these periodically:
+
+```text
+free -m
+systemctl show pibo-web.service -p MemoryCurrent -p MemoryPeak -p MemorySwapCurrent -p MemorySwapPeak
+systemctl show pibo-web-dev.service -p MemoryCurrent -p MemoryPeak -p MemorySwapCurrent -p MemorySwapPeak
+docker ps
+docker stats --no-stream
+ps -eo pid,comm,rss,vsz,args --sort=-rss | head
+```
+
+Keep recent snapshots in a small rotating log. This would make the next incident easier to diagnose.
+
+## Recommended code mitigations
+
+### 1. Add idle eviction for `RoutedSession`s
+
+Add last-used tracking to `PiboSessionRouter.sessions`.
+
+Policy concept:
+
+```text
+if a RoutedSession is idle,
+not processing,
+has no queued messages,
+has no active stream requirement,
+and lastUsedAt is older than N minutes:
+  await session.dispose()
+  sessions.delete(id)
+```
+
+This should be conservative at first. For example, evict after 15-30 minutes of inactivity.
+
+Success criteria:
+
+- active runtime count does not grow without bound;
+- old sessions can be reopened from persisted Pi JSONL / SQLite state;
+- sending a message to an evicted session recreates the runtime safely.
+
+### 2. Add memory diagnostics endpoint or CLI
+
+Expose debug data such as:
+
+```text
+process.memoryUsage()
+active routed session count
+per-session:
+  piboSessionId
+  processing
+  queuedMessages
+  streaming
+  activeTools
+  estimated message count
+  estimated message bytes
+  lastUsedAt
+traceCache entries
+estimated traceCache bytes
+liveListeners count
+activeEventStreams count
+outputCompactor buffer counts
+```
+
+This should be protected as a debug/admin endpoint or CLI command.
+
+### 3. Avoid `SessionManager.list()` during runtime open
+
+When opening a known Pi session, avoid scanning all JSONL files if possible.
+
+Current risk:
+
+```ts
+SessionManager.list(cwd).find(...)
+```
+
+Preferred direction:
+
+```text
+find/open by known piSessionId through a direct path lookup or indexed metadata table
+```
+
+This reduces both latency and memory spikes.
+
+### 4. Bound trace cache by bytes
+
+Current cache limit:
+
+```text
+24 entries
+```
+
+Add a byte budget, for example:
+
+```text
+max entries: 24
+max estimated bytes: N MB
+```
+
+Evict oldest entries until both limits are satisfied.
+
+### 5. Move large tool outputs out of hot memory paths
+
+Long-term, large tool outputs should be represented as:
+
+```text
+preview inline
+payload reference for full content
+full payload stored externally or compressed
+```
+
+This applies to:
+
+- active runtime messages;
+- trace read models;
+- event tables;
+- UI payloads.
+
+### 6. Audit output compactor flush paths
+
+Ensure these buffers are cleared on all terminal conditions:
+
+```text
+assistant delta buffers
+thinking delta buffers
+tool execution update snapshots
+```
+
+Terminal conditions should include:
+
+- message finished;
+- session error;
+- abort;
+- kill;
+- dispose;
+- stream/provider failure.
+
+### 7. Add pressure-aware request behavior
+
+If memory is high, avoid expensive optional work:
+
+- skip trace cache population;
+- skip raw event tails;
+- avoid loading full catalogs on navigation;
+- reduce bootstrap payload;
+- return degraded navigation response rather than freezing.
+
+## Relationship to the earlier data-system performance report
+
+The older performance findings still matter:
+
+- Bootstrap does too much work.
+- Missing titles trigger JSONL scans.
+- Unread counts are expensive.
+- Event data and payloads are duplicated.
+- SQLite files and WAL files are bloated.
+
+Those issues create slow requests and temporary allocations. They can contribute to memory pressure.
+
+However, the VM incident points to a broader stability problem:
+
+```text
+expensive request paths + retained active runtimes + unbounded compute containers + no service memory limits
+```
+
+The immediate stability fix should focus on memory isolation and active runtime cleanup, not only query performance.
+
+## Priority plan
+
+### Priority 0: Protect the VM
+
+- Add Docker memory limits for compute workers.
+- Add systemd memory limits for main/dev/fallback gateways.
+- Fix or constrain fallback so it cannot double production memory use.
+- Reap stale workers automatically.
+
+### Priority 1: Make memory visible
+
+- Add process/router memory diagnostics.
+- Add host memory snapshots.
+- Track active routed sessions and estimated message bytes.
+
+### Priority 2: Stop unbounded runtime retention
+
+- Add idle eviction for `RoutedSession`s.
+- Add explicit cleanup on tab/session close where possible.
+- Verify reopen-from-persistence behavior.
+
+### Priority 3: Reduce memory spikes
+
+- Remove JSONL scans from navigation and runtime open paths.
+- Split bootstrap.
+- Materialize unread counts.
+- Bound trace cache by bytes.
+
+### Priority 4: Reduce payload pressure
+
+- Store large tool outputs outside hot tables and active list responses.
+- Keep previews inline and load full payloads on demand.
+
+## Final conclusion
+
+The crash was most likely caused by system-wide memory and swap exhaustion. The strongest evidence is 99.99% swap usage, about 17 MB available memory, and a load average above 50 shortly before the VM restart.
+
+The highest-risk contributors are:
+
+1. Docker compute workers run without memory limits.
+2. `pibo-web.service` can reach 1.9-2.8 GiB memory peaks.
+3. `pibo-web-fallback.service` can run alongside the main gateway and has also reached high memory peaks.
+4. Active `RoutedSession`s keep full Agent/Pi runtime state in memory and are not automatically evicted.
+5. Bootstrap and runtime-open paths can create large temporary allocations through JSONL scans and event aggregation.
+
+The fastest path to stability is to isolate memory first, then add runtime eviction and diagnostics, then reduce heavy navigation and payload paths.
