+---
+title: PRD - Pibo Workflow MVP
+version: 0.3
+date_created: 2026-05-07
+last_updated: 2026-05-08
+owner: Pibo
+status: draft
+source_specs:
+  - spec/spec-product-projects-area.md
+tags: [prd, product, workflows, projects, sessions, tracing, persistence, mvp]
+---
+
+# PRD: Pibo Workflow MVP
+
+## 1. Summary
+
+Pibo needs a small Workflow layer that owns project process logic. Today, Sessions carry most of the visible work, but Sessions are runtime contexts, not process models. The Workflow MVP introduces a Pibo-owned process layer with Workflow definitions, durable Workflow Runs, explicit nodes and transitions, local persistence, Workflow Trace events, and links to Pibo Sessions. It appears first in a new Projects tab that is a 1:1 copy of the Sessions tab with Project and Workflow extras. Projects must remain a full Session experience: Project Sessions use the normal session tree, terminal/transcript view, trace controls, and composer.
+
+The first product workflow is `standard-project`. It covers normal coding work: spec, implementation, execution, validation, retry loop, user feedback, system update, completion, failure, and discard.
+
+This PRD translates `spec/spec-architecture-workflow-mvp.md` into product requirements for the first shippable feature.
+
+## 2. Problem
+
+Pibo cannot reliably explain or manage multi-step project work if the process state lives only in Sessions or runtime traces.
+
+Users and agents need to answer simple questions:
+
+- What workflow is running?
+- Which step is active?
+- Which Session or runtime did the work?
+- Why did the workflow retry, wait, fail, or complete?
+- What does the user need to approve, change, or discard?
+- Which worker, worktree, or Session artifacts remain?
+
+Runtime traces show what an agent or terminal did. They do not define the product process. Pibo needs a Workflow Run record and Workflow Trace stream above runtime traces.
+
+## 3. Goals
+
+- Create a Pibo-native Workflow foundation for Projects V1.
+- Add Projects as a new tab that copies the Sessions tab layout, behavior, sidebar controls, session tree, selected-session pane, terminal/transcript, trace controls, and composer.
+- Keep the same green Personal Chat row at the top of the Projects sidebar.
+- Replace the Rooms section below Personal Chat with Projects.
+- Keep Project creation, selection, editing, archiving, restoring, and deletion inside Projects routes.
+- Keep Workflow definitions code/plugin-registered in the MVP.
+- Persist Workflow Runs and Workflow Trace events locally.
+- Link Workflow Runs to main and sub Pibo Sessions.
+- Run a first `standard-project` workflow skeleton.
+- Show enough Workflow state for Chat Web and debug tools to explain progress without replacing the selected Project Session surface.
+- Support user feedback actions: approve, request changes, and discard.
+- Support bounded retries and clear failure reasons.
+- Avoid adopting a third-party workflow framework as the V1 core.
+
+## 4. Non-goals
+
+- No visual workflow graph editor in V1.
+- No Context Files/settings-style Projects layout.
+- No Workflow-only Projects dashboard that removes the Session terminal/transcript, trace controls, or composer.
+- No reduced Project sidebar that omits Room-equivalent archive, restore, delete, active/archived grouping, or mobile behavior.
+- No redirect from Project creation to the Sessions tab.
+- No full durable replay engine in V1.
+- No direct adoption of LangGraph.js, XState, DBOS, OpenWorkflow, or another framework as the core engine.
+- No distributed workflow worker system beyond existing Pibo Docker worker integration.
+- No arbitrary graph mutation during a run.
+- No full Research Workflow implementation.
+- No general agent-callable workflow tool until usage enforcement and tracing are stable.
+- No final long-term schema guarantee.
+
+## 5. Users And Jobs
+
+### 5.1 Primary Users
+
+- **Pibo user doing project work**: starts a project task, watches progress, reviews results, requests changes, approves, or discards.
+- **Pibo operator/developer**: debugs Workflow Runs, traces transitions, inspects linked Sessions and workers, and verifies cleanup.
+- **Future agent caller**: starts allowed workflows as tools after V1 hardens usage and policy checks.
+
+### 5.2 Jobs To Be Done
+
+- As a user, I want to start a project task, open its Project Session, chat with it, watch the terminal/transcript, inspect traces, and see which workflow step is active.
+- As a user, I want to approve, request changes, or discard a completed attempt, so I control whether Pibo keeps the result.
+- As a developer, I want every node, transition, retry, wait, failure, and cleanup action recorded, so I can debug workflow behavior.
+- As a developer, I want Workflow Runs linked to Pibo Sessions, so runtime traces remain useful but no longer own process state.
+- As a future agent caller, I want workflows to declare usage modes, so only approved contexts can start them.
+
+## 6. Product Scope
+
+### 6.1 Workflow Foundation
+
+The MVP must add the product foundation for Workflows:
+
+- Workflow Registry
+- Workflow Definition
+- Workflow Runner
+- Workflow Run Store
+- Workflow Trace Store
+- Session/Project Bridge
+- internal Workflow API surface
+
+The first implementation may expose only internal service calls and debug CLI reads. The product shape must leave room for Chat Web and future agent tools.
+
+### 6.2 Standard Project Workflow
+
+The MVP must register `standard-project` as the first workflow type. Its first usage mode should be `session-only`.
+
+The workflow models this flow:
+
+```text
+spec -> implementation -> execution -> test -> loop -> user_feedback -> system_update -> completed
+                                      \-> failed
+user_feedback --request_changes--> implementation
+user_feedback --discard--> discarded
+```
+
+The workflow may begin with a skeleton implementation if every state transition and trace event is persisted.
+
+### 6.3 User Feedback
+
+When the run reaches `user_feedback`, Pibo must expose three actions:
+
+- `approve`
+- `request_changes` with a reason
+- `discard` with an optional reason
+
+Approval moves the run toward `system_update`. Request changes loops back to implementation. Discard moves the run to `discarded` and records the reason.
+
+### 6.4 Trace And Status Read Model
+
+The MVP must provide a read model that can answer:
+
+- current Workflow status,
+- current state and node,
+- main Session and sub-Session links,
+- node timeline,
+- transition timeline,
+- runtime trace correlation,
+- retry count,
+- waiting action prompt,
+- failure or discard reason.
+
+Chat Web can start with a compact status surface. Debug tooling must expose enough detail to validate the Workflow system before richer UI work.
+
+## 7. User Experience Requirements
+
+### 7.1 Starting Work
+
+A user starts project work from a Project context. Pibo creates a Workflow Run for `standard-project`, creates or attaches a main Pibo Session, initializes state, and records `workflow.created` and `workflow.started`.
+
+The user should see that work has entered the first stage inside the normal selected Project Session surface. The first UI may show compact workflow status, but it must still show the Session terminal/transcript and composer.
+
+### 7.1.1 Projects Tab Parity
+
+The Projects tab must look and behave like the Sessions tab before Workflow extras are added. It must not use the Context Files layout.
+
+Required sidebar order:
+
+```text
+Personal Chat        // green row, same as Sessions
+Projects             // replaces Rooms
+Project Sessions     // replaces/renames Sessions where useful
+```
+
+Creating a Project must navigate to a Projects route such as `/projects/:projectId`. It must not navigate to `/rooms/:roomId`, `/sessions/:piboSessionId`, or switch to the Sessions tab.
+
+Parity includes the concrete controls users already rely on in Sessions:
+
+- Project rows must support edit, archive, restore, and delete with the same affordances as Room rows.
+- Project Sessions must support create, select, rename, archive, restore, and delete with the same affordances as Sessions.
+- The active and archived sections must exist for Projects and Project Sessions where the equivalent Sessions UI has them.
+- The Project Session tree must render Main Sessions and Sub-Sessions with the same nesting and selection behavior as Sessions.
+- The main pane must be the normal selected-Session pane: terminal/transcript, session-view selector, trace controls, raw-events controls, and composer.
+- Workflow controls must be additive. They may appear in a header, side panel, or toolbar, but they must not replace the selected-Session pane.
+
+### 7.2 Tracking Progress
+
+Pibo should present progress from the Workflow Run, not Session-local state.
+
+Minimum visible fields:
+
+- Workflow type: `standard-project`
+- status: pending, running, waiting, completed, failed, or discarded
+- current state or step
+- retry count when retries occur
+- linked main Session
+- latest failure or waiting reason when present
+
+### 7.3 Reviewing Results
+
+At `user_feedback`, Pibo should prompt the user for approval. The user can approve, request changes, or discard.
+
+The system must record the decision as a Workflow Trace event. The trace must include the actor and reason when available.
+
+### 7.4 Failure And Discard
+
+When a run fails or is discarded, the user should see the reason and relevant linked artifacts. Pibo should not hide whether workers, worktrees, or Sessions remain.
+
+## 8. Functional Requirements
+
+- **PRD-WF-UI-001**: Chat Web MUST keep the existing Sessions tab available and unchanged while Projects is introduced.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-002**: Chat Web MUST add a Projects tab next to Sessions.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-003**: The Projects tab MUST be a 1:1 structural and behavioral copy of the Sessions tab, with Workflow extras added after parity is in place.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-004**: The Projects sidebar MUST show the same green Personal Chat row at the top that the Sessions sidebar shows.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-005**: Below Personal Chat, the Projects sidebar MUST show Projects where Sessions shows Rooms.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-006**: The Projects tab MUST NOT use the Context Files/settings-style layout as its primary UI.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-007**: Project create/select/edit/archive/restore/delete actions MUST remain in the Projects area and MUST navigate only to Projects routes.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-008**: Project rows MUST expose Room-equivalent edit, archive, restore, and delete controls, adapted to Project labels and safety copy.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-009**: Project Session rows MUST expose Session-equivalent create, select, rename, archive, restore, and delete controls.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-010**: Project Sessions MUST render in the same active/archived tree structure as Sessions, including Main Session and Sub-Session nesting.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-011**: Selecting a Project Session MUST open the normal selected-Session main pane with terminal/transcript, session-view selector, trace controls, raw-events controls, and composer.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-012**: The Project Session composer MUST preserve the same slash commands, draft persistence, history, send behavior, disabled states, and error handling as the Sessions composer.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-013**: Workflow selection, Workflow status, and user-feedback actions MUST be additive controls around the selected Project Session surface.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-014**: Projects MUST NOT replace the selected Project Session surface with only a Workflow status card, dashboard, or settings-style form.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-015**: Project selected-session navigation MUST use Projects routes such as `/projects/:projectId/sessions/:piboSessionId`.
+- **PRD-WF-UI-016**: Project and Project Session deletion MUST show confirmation text that explains whether Sessions, Workflow Runs, worktrees, and Docker workers remain, are archived, or are deleted.
+
+- **PRD-WF-001**: Pibo MUST provide a Workflow Registry for code/plugin-registered Workflow definitions.
+- **PRD-WF-002**: A Workflow definition MUST declare id, version, usage, initial state, nodes, and edges.
+- **PRD-WF-003**: The registry MUST reject duplicate workflow id/version pairs.
+- **PRD-WF-004**: The registry or runner MUST validate node ids, edge ids, edge endpoints, initial state, terminal states, deterministic priorities, usage mode, and bounded retry policy.
+- **PRD-WF-005**: Starting a workflow MUST create a durable Workflow Run record.
+- **PRD-WF-006**: A Workflow Run MUST persist workflow id, workflow version, usage, owner scope, status, current state, retry counters, serializable state data, timestamps, and initiator.
+- **PRD-WF-007**: A Workflow Run MAY link to a Project and MUST be able to link to one or more Pibo Sessions.
+- **PRD-WF-008**: Session links MUST distinguish main Sessions from sub-Sessions.
+- **PRD-WF-009**: The runner MUST emit trace events for workflow creation, workflow start, node start, node completion, node failure, transition evaluation, transition taken, state change, runtime start, runtime completion, waiting, resume, user feedback, retry, cleanup, completion, failure, and discard.
+- **PRD-WF-010**: Trace events MUST be append-only and ordered per Workflow Run.
+- **PRD-WF-011**: The runner MUST enforce Workflow usage mode at start time.
+- **PRD-WF-012**: The runner MUST support bounded retries.
+- **PRD-WF-013**: Exhausted retries MUST move the run to `failed` unless an error edge handles the failure.
+- **PRD-WF-014**: Runtime-backed nodes MUST correlate Workflow Trace events with Pibo Session ids and runtime trace metadata when available.
+- **PRD-WF-015**: User nodes MUST support a `waiting` state and store expected user actions.
+- **PRD-WF-016**: `standard-project` MUST exist as a registered Workflow definition.
+- **PRD-WF-017**: `standard-project` SHOULD start as `session-only`.
+- **PRD-WF-018**: `standard-project` MUST support the states or nodes `spec`, `implementation`, `execution`, `test`, `loop`, `user_feedback`, `system_update`, `completed`, `failed`, and `discarded`.
+- **PRD-WF-019**: `standard-project` MUST support approve, request-changes-with-reason, and discard actions at `user_feedback`.
+- **PRD-WF-020**: Cleanup and destructive system-update actions MUST require explicit confirmation before execution.
+- **PRD-WF-021**: Workflow state machines MUST live on Workflows, not Projects, Rooms, Sessions, Agents, or Runtimes.
+- **PRD-WF-022**: The MVP MUST use local-first persistence.
+- **PRD-WF-023**: The MVP MUST NOT add a third-party workflow framework as a core dependency by default.
+
+## 9. Data And Persistence Requirements
+
+The MVP should persist Workflow data in local SQLite under the Pibo data path.
+
+Minimum tables:
+
+```text
+workflow_runs
+workflow_trace_events
+workflow_session_links
+```
+
+The persistence layer must store JSON payloads only when they are serializable. It must reject functions, class instances, and unserializable state values before writing persisted state.
+
+The `workflow_trace_events` table must enforce unique `(workflow_run_id, sequence)` pairs.
+
+## 10. API And Tooling Requirements
+
+The first product API may be internal, but it should follow this conceptual shape:
+
+```ts
+startWorkflow(input: StartWorkflowInput): Promise<WorkflowRun>;
+resumeWorkflow(input: ResumeWorkflowInput): Promise<WorkflowRun>;
+getWorkflowRun(id: string): Promise<WorkflowRun>;
+listWorkflowRuns(filter: WorkflowRunFilter): Promise<WorkflowRun[]>;
+getWorkflowTrace(workflowRunId: string): Promise<WorkflowTraceEvent[]>;
+discardWorkflowRun(id: string, reason: string): Promise<WorkflowRun>;
+```
+
+The MVP should also include debug CLI read commands for Workflow Runs and Workflow traces before or alongside Chat Web UI work.
+
+Agent-callable tools come later. They must wait until usage modes, policy checks, and trace behavior are stable.
+
+## 11. UX/UI Requirements
+
+Chat Web should eventually show Workflow progress from Workflow Run state.
+
+MVP UI can be minimal, but it must be a complete Session experience:
+
+- match the Sessions tab layout and behavior before adding extras,
+- show the green Personal Chat row at the top of the Projects sidebar,
+- show Projects where Sessions shows Rooms,
+- support Project edit, archive, restore, and delete,
+- show Project Sessions where Sessions shows Sessions,
+- support Project Session create, select, rename, archive, restore, and delete,
+- show Main Sessions and Sub-Sessions in the normal tree,
+- show the selected Project Session terminal/transcript, session-view selector, trace controls, raw-events controls, and composer,
+- show active Workflow type when useful,
+- show current status and state,
+- show waiting prompts and allowed user actions,
+- show failure and discard reasons,
+- reuse existing runtime/terminal trace views rather than linking away from or hiding them,
+- distinguish main Session from sub-Sessions when visible.
+
+The first implementation may rely on debug CLI and a compact Chat Web status read model if full graph visualization would slow the MVP.
+
+## 12. Security, Safety, And Policy
+
+- Workflow start must enforce declared usage mode.
+- `standard-project` starts as `session-only` unless a later spec approves agent-started runs.
+- Destructive cleanup requires explicit confirmation.
+- Runtime nodes must use existing Pibo Session Router and profile boundaries.
+- Execution-capable project work must use isolated workspaces and Docker workers through existing Pibo systems.
+- The implementation must not copy third-party project code without explicit approval.
+
+## 13. Success Metrics
+
+The MVP is successful when:
+
+- A function-only Workflow Run can start, transition, complete, and persist trace events.
+- A Workflow Run can link to a main Pibo Session.
+- A runtime-backed node can correlate Workflow Trace events with a Pibo Session.
+- `standard-project` can run through its skeleton flow and reach `completed`, `failed`, or `discarded`.
+- A user feedback step can pause, resume, approve, request changes, or discard.
+- Debug tooling can show a run's state, Session links, and ordered trace events.
+- A developer can explain every retry, failure, and state change from trace data alone.
+- No core third-party workflow framework is added.
+
+## 14. Release Plan
+
+### Phase 1: Workflow Core
+
+- Add core types.
+- Add Workflow Registry.
+- Add definition validator.
+- Add function-node runner.
+- Add local run and trace persistence.
+
+Exit criteria: a small function-only workflow runs and persists ordered traces.
+
+### Phase 2: User Nodes And Session Links
+
+- Add `waiting` status.
+- Add resume path.
+- Add user feedback event recording.
+- Add Workflow Run to Pibo Session links.
+
+Exit criteria: a workflow can pause for user input, resume, and show its main Session link.
+
+### Phase 3: Runtime Node Adapter
+
+- Add runtime-backed node execution through existing Pibo Session routing.
+- Correlate runtime trace metadata with Workflow Trace events.
+- Record worktree and Docker worker metadata when available.
+
+Exit criteria: a runtime node can start or reuse a Pibo Session and record trace correlation.
+
+### Phase 4: Standard Project Skeleton
+
+- Register `standard-project` V1.
+- Implement core states and transitions.
+- Add bounded implementation/execution/test retry loop.
+- Add approve, request changes, and discard behavior.
+
+Exit criteria: `standard-project` can complete, fail, or discard with traceable reasons.
+
+### Phase 5: Minimal Product Surface
+
+- Add debug CLI commands for runs and traces.
+- Add compact Chat Web status/read model fields.
+- Link Workflow status to existing runtime trace views.
+
+Exit criteria: users and developers can inspect Workflow progress without reading raw database rows.
+
+## 15. Dependencies
+
+- Existing Pibo Session Router.
+- Existing profile/runtime system.
+- Existing runtime and terminal traces.
+- Existing project/session workspace and Docker compute worker system.
+- Local Pibo data path and SQLite support.
+- Projects area product model.
+- Existing Sessions tab sidebar/main-panel layout as the required UI baseline.
+
+## 16. Risks And Mitigations
+
+| Risk | Impact | Mitigation |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| Workflow engine grows too large for V1 | Delays Projects V1 | Start with function, user, and simple runtime nodes only. |
+| Session and Workflow ownership blur | Product state becomes hard to debug | Keep state machine and transition data only on Workflow Runs. |
+| Runtime nodes duplicate work after restart | Duplicate workers or side effects | Persist runtime/session correlation metadata before and after runtime starts. |
+| Trace volume becomes noisy | UI and debugging become harder | Store full trace events, but build compact read models for UI. |
+| Third-party framework adoption pulls product boundaries away from Pibo | Architecture conflict | Treat assessed frameworks as reference-only until dependency review. |
+| User feedback actions are unsafe | Accidental destructive cleanup | Require explicit confirmation for destructive cleanup and discard side effects. |
+
+## 17. Acceptance Criteria
+
+- A registered workflow definition with function nodes can run from start to completion.
+- Invalid definitions fail validation before they can run.
+- Workflow Runs persist status, state, retry counters, owner scope, and state data.
+- Workflow Trace events persist in order and include node, transition, state, retry, wait, feedback, failure, and completion events.
+- Workflow Runs can link to main and sub Pibo Sessions.
+- The Projects tab visually and behaviorally matches the Sessions tab and includes the green Personal Chat row.
+- Creating, editing, archiving, restoring, deleting, and selecting a Project stays under `/projects...` and does not redirect to Sessions.
+- Project Sessions can be created, selected, renamed, archived, restored, deleted, and nested as Sub-Sessions using the same interaction model as Sessions.
+- Selecting a Project Session shows the normal terminal/transcript, trace controls, and composer.
+- `standard-project` is registered with `session-only` usage.
+- `standard-project` can enter `user_feedback` and accept approve, request changes, and discard actions.
+- Failed and discarded runs preserve reasons.
+- Runtime-backed nodes record Session correlation when available.
+- Debug tooling can list runs and show ordered traces.
+- The implementation adds no core third-party workflow framework dependency.
+
+## 18. Open Questions
+
+- Should the first Workflow SQLite store be `.pibo/pibo-events.sqlite`, `.pibo/workflows.sqlite`, or another existing store?
+- Should Workflow definitions register through the plugin registry immediately, or through a small internal registry first?
+- Which `standard-project` nodes should be `function` nodes in the first slice?
+- Which `standard-project` nodes must be `runtime` nodes before the MVP is useful?
+- How should waiting Workflow Runs migrate when a definition version changes?
+- What is the first Chat Web UI for user feedback actions?
+- How should nested Workflow Runs appear beside sub-Sessions in trace views?
+- How much checkpointing is needed before runtime-backed nodes can resume safely after process restart?
